While looking for interesting MovableType plugins I discovered <a href="http://kung-foo.tv">kung-foo.tv</a> (this is probably where I first saw both the BlogTimes plugin in use as well as the "Last 10 Google Referrers" script).  I noticed that the webblog author was working on a piece of software called Kung-Log.  Well, Kung-Log has since been renamed "<a href="http://www.kung-foo.tv/ecto/">ecto</a>."  After hearing many good things about Kung-Log/ecto I decided yesterday to try it out here at work.  Unfortunately, ecto could not get the list of "Entries and Drafts" from the MovableType webblog I'm using here at work.  This is troublesome because I'm looking into finding a way to make it easy for non-html people to use the same webblog at work (using the webblog for a type of error tracking and information collecting).

ecto was giving me error -65795 in a report that looked something like this:

<div class="code">Query:
{blogid = 4; password = ********; username = "********"; }
Response:
{
 "/FaultCode" = -65794; 
 "/FaultExtra" = {domain = -1; error = -65795; msg = "Encountered string encoding error"; }; 
 "/FaultString" = "/CFStreamFault"; 
 "/kWSHTTPResponseMessage" = &lt;NSCFType: 0x154b470&gt;; 
 "/kWSResultIsFault" = 1; 
}</div>

I googled for it and came up with nothing.  I decided to search for the error code on the in the MovableType User Forums and came up with <a href="http://www.movabletype.org/support/index.php?act=ST&#38;f=10&#38;t=15682&#38;hl=65794&#38;s=580fdebd3c84935fcdd8a867ab20e019">this thread</a>.  The last post in the thread, by Adriaant, describes the problem.  

This is the explanation in my own words:
Characters in the posts are not properly formatted using the accepted "html" code and these symbols cannot be properly interpreted by the Apple WebServicesCore that ecto uses.  For example, the ampersand symbol (&#38;) must be coded as "&amp;" and not simply as "&#38;".  (This <a href="http://www.kung-foo.tv/blog/archives/000285.php">kung-foo.tv post</a> confirms and further explains the problem.)

In order to get ecto to properly work with my weblog at work, I had to go through every post and look for characters that would seem to need the proper coding.  I found that &rsquo; needed special coding (&rsquo;).  To know the proper "code" to use to make these symbols, I found these two pages:  <a href="http://www.evolt.org/article/comment/17/21234/">Simple Character Entity Chart</a> and <a href="http://www.jovino.com/stuff/entities.html">HTML Character Entities</a>.  This second page can also be useful for anyone doing C/C++ coding as it includes the hex equivalents for the full ASCII / ISO 8859-1 character set.

So if my posts start to contain a bunch of Greek letters(&phi;&omega;&psi;&mu;&xi;), you'll know what pages inspired me.

